	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">pragma wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">So has anyone attempted to mold their own NES cart?  Are there any (legal) issues with making a replica of a standard Nintendo cartridge</div><br />Industrial designs such as the shape of a Game Pak are subject to design patent law, not copyright law. Nintendo's design patents have expired. However, it's still wise to make a distinctive design for your cartridge.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Personally, I never liked the idea of tearing up an existing cartridge since there will only ever be so many of 'em out there.</div>
<br />If you're not willing to send technicians out to all your customers' houses to cut pin 4 of frontloaders that have those extra diodes to block the -5V trick, then you're going to need to cut up existing cartridges to get lockout chips anyway.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


